Within a few hours after the vaccine was administered, I felt unwell and became progressively worse. For 36 hours after the vaccine, I experienced a crisis of energy, fatigue, and body soreness. It subsided after 36 hours. I expected that was a reasonable response for my already highly sensitive and overactive immune system (autoimmunity). What I didn't expect was two weeks later to erupt with shingles. I have had shingles twice in my earlier adult life, so I am familiar with the symptoms. This course has gotten worse over the last 2-1/2 weeks. There was no other change in my low-stress life with the exception of the Covid vaccine. I had been working hard to reduce my inflammation already with diet and lifestyle changes for the last 2 years with great success. It seems the vaccine triggered my immune system in such a profound way it pulled this dormant virus out. I was concerned to get the vaccine because of my autoimmunity but decided to do it anyway, hoping for the best. I don't know if it's advisable for people with existing immune conditions to tax their system this way. I know I'm paying a high price.
HISTORY: Autoimmunity and chronic inflammation, hormonal imbalance, blood sugar instability

The week prior to delivery (3/22), I started feeling shortness of breath and a headache. I thought it was just normal pregnancy symptoms. That Friday (3/26), I noticed swelling in my ankles. I am a teacher so I asked my school nurse to check my blood pressure; it was high (for me) around 144/88. She said I should call my OB and let them know. I did, and they said to rest for the weekend and they'd see me on Tuesday for my 29 week appointment.   We had a weekend trip planned. We took our son there. The next night, I didn't feel right. My belly felt hard to me and I wasn't feeling my daughter move as much, but soon after, I went to sleep. Our two year old son woke us up crying around midnight, and I noticed that I started bleeding when I went to the bathroom. My husband drove me straight to the emergency room. I was diagnosed with sudden and severe preeclampsia. My fibrinogen levels were 100% indicative of a placental abruption. They called the transport team in from hospital so they could transfer my daughter immediately after birth. At 5:57 am on 3/28, my daughter was born via emergency c-section. She is currently fighting everyday at the NICU in the hospital.  On Friday, 4/2 I was readmitted for severe preeclampsia to hospital. My blood pressure was 190/115. I had to receive another round of magnesium sulfate. I was released from the hospital on Sunday, 4/4.
LAB_DATA: Several tests were performed on me. These can be released to the CDC per their request.
OTHER_MEDS: Prenatal Vitamin Vitamin D Supplement (50,000 IUI - 1x per week)

Patient has history of endometrial uterine ablation nearly 8 years ago.  Interestingly, the day after receiving her Jansen Covid vaccine she had vaginal bleeding which lasted approximately 24 hours. She has not had any vaginal bleeding in the past 8 years since her ablation.  She has also described frequent nosebleeds over the past few days since the vaccination. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Sore arm and fatigue all day after vaccine. At some point in the middle of the night, roughly midnight or 1am I woke up feeling sick. I was extremely dizzy to the point I could hardly stand up. I was nauseous and felt dehydrated. My head was pounding and I had a fever. My fever broke around 2am and ai broke into a sweat. I had terrible chills. The upper part of my arm was hot to the touch and swollen and red. My arm was very painful, it hurt to even barely touch it.  I had to call in to work for the day. I couldn't get out of bed until 1pm. By 2pm I was able to stand and walk but was still experiencing chills and pain and the head ache. By evening I was about 50% better. The next morning I only had the red, sore arm and felt fatigue that whole day. I was at about 80% okay. Sunday I was fine. The soreness in my arm lasted five days.
10 days after injection, I started having ringing in my ears. It is a high pitch ringing in both ears that is constant. I've never had this before and continue to have it to this day.
LAB_DATA: Conducted a hearing test and everything came back normal. ENT said ears looked normal. Took 30 mg of prednisone for 5 days and did not help.

When I got my Vaccine I watched the man giving it to me pull the needle out of my arm while he was still pushing and it squirted on my arm, went down my arm, and dripped on the floor. I said something to the man that gave me my injection. He tried to say it was the alcohol as he wiped my arm. I told him No it wasn't! I watched him pull the needle out of my arm, while still pushing. I watched the stream come out of the needle, roll down my arm & drop off of my elbow to the floor! The man still tried to say it was the alcohol while he wiped on my arm. This is not true. I am a Registered Medical Assistant and given various injections myself in physician's offices over the years so, I know what I saw and I know %100 I did not receive the full vaccine.  I asked to speak to a supervisor. The supervisor. She took my paper and said she would call me in 4 weeks. She said all they could do is offer to run an antibody test in 4 weeks. This supervisor was not there when I was given the vaccine. She came when I asked for a supervisor.   This is the email I received from CDC help - Your vaccination provider will determine whether more than half of the dose was administered. If you received more than half the dose of a COVID-19 vaccine, you do not need to repeat the dose. If less than half of the dose was administered or the proportion of the dose you received cannot be estimated, you should immediately receive the recommended dose in your opposite arm.     If you received too small of a dose of COVID-19 vaccine, your healthcare provider should report this to the Vaccine Adverse Event Reporting System (VAERS). Healthcare providers are required to report to VAERS any COVID-19 vaccine administration errors,    Which I did not receive anything.  This is the response from the Health Department.  From the supervisor that talked to me the day of the vaccine said - Again, we want to apologize that you had this experience. I have since reached out to the CDC and this is the information they pointed me back to. It is not recommended to perform antibody testing at this time to assess for immunity to COVID-19 following the COVID-19 vaccination because the variable sensitivity of tests. If antibody testing is performed following vaccination, additional doses of the same or different COVID19 vaccines are not recommended based on antibody test results at this time. Unfortunately, they are not recommending any further action at this time. Here is the link to the CDC website for further information.  I would like to know what needs to be done.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient states on Friday, 4/9, he went to the pharmacy to receive his J&J Covid-19 vaccine. He states on Saturday morning, his R nostril began to bleed, and continued to bleed until Monday. He states on Wednesday, 4/7, he noticed oral sores that at first were not painful, but large. He was worried about it interfering with his shot, but because he had waited so long to get it, he decided to proceed anyway. He denies any fever or chills, no frank diarrhea, but occasional loose stools, without blood seen. He denies HA, vision changes, or focal neuro deficits. On Sunday, 4/11, the patient ended up going to ED to evaluate his epistaxis, the MD attributed it to his elevated BP, the patient reports it being 160s/90s. They gave him new BP medications, which he took, but when he saw the Dr., he instructed the patient not to keep taking his BP meds. When asking the patient if anything correlates with foods he eats, the only thing he can pinpoint it to, would be pico de gallo. He states it has irritated his mouth before. He also reports recently taking his wife's supplement (unknown name) but thinks it is for cholesterol. He took that approximately 1 week ago. No new changes in food habits, mouthwash, or toothpaste. He states once his sores began to get a little painful, he went to buy a special mouthwash for oral sores (unsure name). His only reported allergy is to Lisinopril, which his reaction was a whole body rash.    He states they did not pack his nose or do anything for his epistaxis at the ER, but eventually he let the nostril clot with blood. Now he feels fullness in the nare, but does not want to disturb the clot in fear that it will re-bleed. His wife also noticed a petechial rash that began on his BLE, he is unsure when that started.    He presented to  ED on 4/13, due to his PCP  instructing him to be evaluated when he had outpatient labs done and revealed a PLT count of 4,000. In the ED, the patient had normal vital signs.  He was transfused one unit of PLTs. He also had a negative head CT. He was also started on decadron 40mg PO daily by heme/onc. Patient tells me today his sores are less painful and feel smaller than usual. Heme/onc also ordered 2 IVIG 1,000 mg/kg/day x2 doses.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: The day after the vaccine I ran errands, returned home and started to do chores. In the middle of cleaning, a wave of nausea and sickness fell over me. I had what I am assuming was a strong immune response of the vaccine working: chills, sweating, achey, nausea, no appetite. As the day went on I started to get neck pain, headache, sensitivity to sound and light, back and abdominal pain, and strong painful muscle contractions. The next day I felt better, mainly sore and achey. The day after my symptoms returned (Monday) and I had a very hard time moving or eating or drinking. Tuesday and Wednesday I felt a little better, but still not well. Telemedicine appointment with my doctor on Wednesday, and blood work was drawn which was unremarkable. Thursday was also difficult, and Friday I forced myself to push through to cover office duties at my job. Saturday I felt better and saw a couple of friends, and Sunday I felt better as well until the evening when I felt a lot of neck pain, acheyness and weakness, headache, nausea, tingling and tremors. Monday was a repeat of this, and found if I lay down and don?t move it isn?t as bad. Tuesday was also difficult, a visit to the chiropractor temporarily reduced symptoms for a couple of hours. I also had night sweats and sometimes if standing too long sweats and balance problems. Motrin and Tylenol did not bring much relief, zofran helped with nausea.
LAB_DATA: Blood work done on 4/7/2021 was unremarkable
OTHER_MEDS: Fiasp insulin, synthroid, effexor, vitamin d, zinc, multivitamin, vitamin b 12
HISTORY: Diabetes type 1, Hashimoto?s thyroiditis, Ehlers-Danlos Syndrome, Tarlov cysts
ALLERGIES: Contact allergens your nickel, gold, and cobalt

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I received my first dose of the pfizer vaccine at 11am at the safeway pharmacy. I had consumed several glasses of water in the morning before the event, a cup of yerba mate tea, and a piece of toast. I smoke, and had smoked one cigarette in the morning before my appointment. Just after receiving the vaccine I ate a few pieces of jerky and maybe 15 Jojo potatoes from the safeway deli.  I was advised to wait 15 minutes before leaving. I set an alarm. I bought some food to eat (jojo potatoes and jerky) and waited to leave the site until 11:22am. I felt strange/weird, but this isn't an unusual feeling after receiving any kind of shot/vaccine for me.   I was driving to work and I started to feel just a little bit strange after smoking another cigarette. I got a little nauseous but nothing too bad. Thirty seconds later I started to get dizzy, my ears rang, I felt my blood pressure drop, and I passed out on the interstate going freeway speeds. I woke up around a minute and half later according to my brother who was on the phone. I was treated for injuries at emergency room.
LAB_DATA: Received treatment in the emergency room after the crash. ED Provider notes that it sounds like a vasovagal event, writing, "I think this was a combination of a vasovagal event from Covid vaccine as well as smoking," and adds, "Does not sound like a seizure or cardiogenic syncope. EKG is reassuring. Troponin is reassuring. Electrolytes are reassuring. He is not anemic or hypoglycemic."  I received a CT scan and everything seemed fine.

The day I received the shot, I started to feel severe fatigue, headache, light-headed, and started running a fever about 6 hours after the shot was administered.  The next day (4/6) was worse. Severe fatigue, muscle aches, headache, loss of appetite, fever (101.5 was the highest I notice but seemed to be around 101.1-101.3 all day), and general flu like symptoms. However, I also started experiencing abnormal menstrual bleeding. I am on the Depo shot and have been for some time. Due to this, I do not usually experience any menstrual bleeding so I found this to be a little odd. It was not heavy but it was noticeable and contained quite a few clots.   Day 3 (4/7) was about the same except my fever came down and ranged from 99.8-101.1. Abnormal menstrual bleeding continued. New side effect this day included diarrhea.   Day 4 (4/8) I started to see improvement. No fever (that I could tell). Remaining side effects included mild headache, fatigue, diarrhea, and abnormal menstrual bleeding.   Day 5 (4/9), I had one of the worst nose bleeds I've ever had in my life. I apologize for the graphic description but it lasted about 20 minutes and my bathroom looked like a crime scene after. Blood was pouring out of my left nostril and I threw two large clots that were about the size of slug (or slightly larger than a fun size snickers... I wish I had a better way to describe it). I've had some bad nose bleeds, particularly when I was on Accutane, and this was worse! The rest of the day I felt like I was improving. Energy levels were better. No fever. Menstrual bleeding stopped. Only lingering side effect was mild headache and mild diarrhea.   Since then I've continued to feel better and the diarrhea seems like it's improving.  Mild headache persists. Only new  item is an annoying twitch in my left eye that started on Monday (4/12).
LAB_DATA: None yet. I see my doctor this afternoon.
OTHER_MEDS: Adderall, Depo-provera birth control shot, Zyrtec, Magnesium, Zinc, Vitamin D

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Was observed post Covid-19 immunization for 15 minutes .  During the observation period, she experienced an adverse reaction with the following symptoms:  hives and itching. She came up for check out with the Nurse at the checkout table and informed her of the itching. She was taken to the triage area and given the medications listed below. Vitals taken. After observing her for 15 minutes, she says the itching was getting worse, a 5/10 on the severity scale 1-10 being initially a 4. The redness to her arms, back, back of neck was not fading. Her lips looks puffy. I advised I would need to call for an EMT to come evaluate, she verbalized understanding. I called at 1049 and the EMT arrived to evaluate her at 1100. He noticed swelling to lips, slight tongue swelling and slight swelling to her gums, hives to her bilateral lower legs as well as the redness to her arms, back, back of neck. She mentioned to him the itching to the top lip had resolved. He advised due to her worsening symptoms, he would need to give more medication. At 1108 Benadryl 50 mg IM given; 1115-18 G Saline lock was started in the Rt A/C and he gave her Solumedrol 125 mg IV. He advised she will need to go to the ED for further evaluation and called for an ambulance to transport. Ambulance arrived at 1125 and she was transported to Hospital ED for evaluation. Patient called her father to notify him of the hospital to meet her there.    Actions taken:  Vitals sign taken  EMS called at  1115. Form obtained and completed by Nurse. SYMPTOM_TEXT: I got the vaccine at 4pm at the pharmacy where I work. I had no symptoms except for very mild local injection discomfort but was able to do my usual normal activities. At 2 am that evening, I woke up with  a lot of pain in my legs, I felt they were so heavy to move around in bed. My lower back was extremely painful too, I tried to stand up to walk a bit, the pain was very severe and I couldn?t stand straight, it was very hard to drag my feet, they felt very heavy and my muscled were painful to the touch even. So went back to bed, and was in agony. I had to go to work in the morning to open the store I work at until they find me coverage. Driving was very hard with my painful legs. J reached the store and I was walking very slowly, I couldn?t have a full control over my legs, they were painful waist down, and felt very heavy, when I sat down my muscles were painful wherever pressure was applied to them (from the chair).  Lightheadedness: I felt lightheaded when I woke up from bed at night to try to walk and ease the pain. So decided to go back to bed to prevent falls. At work, while walking and sitting, I had episodes of very light headidness and sat often on the floor and lifted my legs. Measured my blood pressure on 3 occasions it was 90/50  then 100/50 then 110/60. One time only I fainted where my colleagues put me down and lifted my legs.  At 8am (morning of 3/9/20201) I had a feeling of  heavy breathing. Needed to take deep breath as if my lung muscles were tired and needed to take deep breath to fill them with enough air. At work and because of the increased intensity of muscles pain, I started to breath faster and deeper coz I was in agony   Headache: severe and excruciating headache started from 6am to 12pm on 3/9/21.   Throughout the symptoms, I refused to take medications to let the vaccine run its course. My family drove me back from work coz I was weak and lightheaded and in severe pain at 10.30am. Came home, took one Advil 200mg at 11am. I was completely pain free  at 12pm. Lungs still felt weak, needed to breath deeper for two days but then got better.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I had sparkles in my vision 5 min. after getting my shot. They went away quickly, so I wasn't concerned. I had a little bit of hotness up my neck and a little itchy, but both also were quick to go away. I went home and went to bed without issue. I woke up at 4am crying and in a lot of pain all over my body. I had a crushing headache, my back, arms and legs ached down to the bone. I had a fever of 100.7, and had to call in sick from work. I took 3 ibuprofen and it didn't help stop the pain or fever. I cried myself back to sleep after wreathing in pain for 3 hours. Woke up again crying again and the pain and fever continued on. I drank 2 beers to see if that would help relax my muscles and back around 3pm and by 4pm I finally felt somewhat better, but still couldn't get up out of bed. I had to call my brother over to help me and considered asking him to take me to the hospital several times because the pain was so intense. The spot where I got my shot wasn't inflamed, or if it was I didn't notice. It did seem a little stiff. I managed to fall back asleep and by the time I woke up again the next day around 5am, I felt completely fine. Fever disappeared and the body pain was gone. It was like nothing had ever happened.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Approximately eight hours after receiving the shot, I started getting a headache, body aches, and chills (April 3rd, 8 p.m.).  I went to bed and had severe chills and body sweats for the entire night.  The primary symptom to report is that my heart raced all night.  It felt like it was beating at about 140 to 150 Hz or higher.  When I woke up in the morning, it felt like my chest had been pounded on all night.  The pain was in my sternum area.  The headache and body aches took a little over a day to go away.  The chest pain took a couple of days to die down.  On April 12th, I walked my dogs in the morning and felt out of breath, which isn't normal for me.  In the afternoon, while working at my desk at home, I started getting more and more severe chest pain and then started getting dizzy and felt weak.  I drove myself to the local ER and they tested me for a heart attack.  All tests came back negative.  They suggested going to another facility to get checked for clots or to make an appointment with a cardiologist.  The next day, after talking to a doctor friend, he suggested going to the ER facility to get imaged for clots and to get fully checked out.  No cardiologist appointments were available till the next week.  I went to the ER facility and was there for seven hours getting tested.  They came back and said all test results were negative and that my heart looked fine.  They did not have any suggestions for what might be causing the pain in my chest.
LAB_DATA: EKG, blood work, CT scan of chest.  All tests that were run came back negative.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: About 9 hours after my vaccine, I developed severe chills for 2 hours and a fever of around 100.1, I also had shortness of breath. It finally decreased to about 102 and remained there for about 6 more hours. I had trouble getting up to use the restroom and would feel very dizzy, my temperature dropped midday to about 100. My fever finally broke about 24 hours after my vaccine, but I still lost my appetite and was experiencing body aches and a headache. I couldn't eat anything for about 48 hours after my vaccine, I was able to take small sips of water to help stay hydrated. It took until Saturday (5 days after my vaccine) to feel back to normal. I felt very puffy and swollen the entire week following my vaccine and was very fatigued.

The day after the vaccine (Sunday, 3/21/21), I had severe leg pain--throbbing in both legs.  My legs felt warm to the touch. There was swelling, redness, and pain at the injection site (my left arm) all the way down the left side of my body (under my arm and around my ribs).  I took Acetaminophen, but the pain persisted all day.  The pain in my legs was the worst symptom and it was so painful and uncomfortable that it was impossible to sleep that night.  I've never felt anything like it. I was planning to go to an emergency clinic the next day if the pain continued.  I finally got to sleep in the morning  (Monday, 3/22/21) and slept for several hours.  When I woke up later that day (3/22/21), the pain was gone and I felt normal again.   I was still tired for the rest of the week and I continued to have swelling in my arm at the injection site, but otherwise, no other symptoms.  It took approximately 6 days for the pain and swelling in my arm to feel better.  I did not seek medical attention because the leg pain was gone within 24 hours, but I am concerned now and am wondering if there has been any permanent damage to my circulatory system or heart.  I have noticed that my pulse has been elevated for the last 3 weeks (as compared to normal).

SYMPTOM_TEXT: This is a 19 y.o. female status post 1st dose of Moderna vaccination on 04/14/21 at 130PM. Patient was outside under the tent waiting 15 minutes  post vaccination when she fell out of her chair and onto the ground. Upon arrival, patient was lying face down and unresponsive. 10 seconds later patient regained consciousness, but was lethargic, clammy and pale. Patient is nauseous and vomiting. With assistance, patient was transported via wheelchair inside the modular unit in the  parking lot. Reports eating a cookie this morning. Last meal was last night and it was a bowl of spaghetti.  Patient reports having a syncopal episode and seizure 5 months ago after getting a COVID-19 nasal testing. Denies any medical history, no NKDA, no medications, no recent illness. Initial VS at 1400 was 90/56 HR 52, 02 sats 98% on room air. Denies SOB, denies difficulty breathing, denies chest pain, denies HA, denies dizziness.  VS 1408- 90/56 HR: 57 BPM, RR: 12 BPM, O2 Sats: 98% Room Air VS 1425-91/57 HR 50 BPM, RR: 12 BPM 02 Sats 98% Room Air VS 1440- 94/57 HR: 54 BPM, RR: 12 BPM, 02 Sats: 98% RA  Plan: Syncope and collapse- Patient was evaluated for 1 hour. Patient reports that she was feeling much better and was eager to go back to her room. Her pallor improved, she was AOx3 and speaking in clear sentences. , RN was advised to try patient with sips of clear liquids and provide her some crackers and have patient ambulate prior to discharge. When the nurse was repeating her VS and providing the patient the crackers, patient experienced another syncopal episode, but regained consciousness immediately. VS at 1450:  HR 49 BPM, O2 Sats 99%, BP 82/50.  Because patient experienced another syncopal episode, 911 was dispatched for ER evaluation. Patient asked that I speak to her mother, mother updated on patient's condition and that she needs to go the ER for further evaluation. Mother agrees and verbalizes understanding of care. Spoke to  with the local health department and she reports that this case will need to be reported to VAERS. Patient is being transported by stretcher to the hospital. Will follow up with the patient.   Nausea and Vomiting- Patient refusing Zofran IM, prefers PO. Zofran 4 mg SL given once at 1400 for nausea and vomiting. Nausea and Vomiting improved within 20 minutes. No nausea or vomiting upon discharge from the health center.
CUR_ILL: Patient was diagnosed with COVID-19 on 03/16/2021

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Started out with a headache and dizziness within a few minutes of the vaccine, along with nausea. I stayed put laying down with a lollipop and water bottle along with ice packs on me for about an hour until I was well enough they thought for me to drive back to my dorm. Once I started driving the headache was back but I was driving so I couldn?t do much. Almost pulled over because I was getting over whelmed but ended up making it back to my dorm. Once I got back I changed and laid down in bed hoping to fell better. Things started getting worse from there. Throughout the rest of the day my head ache and dizziness got worse to the point where I was pretty unsteady on my feet. Chills and body aches also started and progressed rapidly despite no fever.  My nausea was present in waves but eventually dissipated around 8 PM.  I tried to go to bed around 11 hoping to sleep off the symptoms. I began tossing and turning. My chills were really bad and it got to the point where my skin was so sensitive that the clothes I was wearing touching and rubbing against my skin were hurting me. I was so dizzy and light headed to the point where it didn?t matter if I was laying down or sitting up, I felt the same, extremely dizzy and lightheaded as if cotton were in my brain or as if it were working too slow. It was like trying to process thoughts through molasses. Then around 1:30 I couldn?t take it anymore and thought maybe a quick shower would help me to at least feel better so I could sleep. When I got in the shower I immediately knew things were worse.  My vision started going black at the edges and black spots in the middle to the point where at certain moments I couldn?t see. I was fighting to stay on my feet and conscious and it was hurting to breathe. I knew I needed to get help so I stumbled to my dorm and collapsed when I got in the doorway to my room. My vision was spotty, my chest was hurting and I could barely breathe.  My hands and feet went numb as well, I was shivering, and my body temperature was a little down to about 98.1 degrees Fahrenheit.   I was transported to a hospital via ambulance my vitals were normal except elevated heart rate and O2 and  was admitted at 2:40 in the morning. I received a chest x ray and  my heart rate was better.  The dizziness was under control by then. I was discharged at 4:50 in the morning.
OTHER_MEDS: Vyvanse Escitalopram Propranolol Birth control pill Myocycline

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 82YM Admit 3/18/21 to hospital for small bowel obstruction within 1 week of  second vaccine dose. PTA bowel obstruction led to a syncopal episode following use of laxative, and several episodes of vomiting in the days prior . Upon admission Patient was receiving conservative therapy for a partial obstruction when he developed increasing shortness of breath.  The patient was transferred to the ICU for worsening respiratory status and eventually developed significant hypercapnic and hypoxemic respiratory failure requiring intubation.  Neurology was consulted for altered mentation in the setting of respiratory failure. Patient with ascending paralysis. MRI of the head and neck as well as CTA were obtained x2. Patient was ultimately diagnosed with Guillain-Barre, variant and received 5 days of Intravenous Immune Globulin therapy.  Patient's small bowel obstruction resolved and ultimately patient required percutaneous tracheostomy tube and gastrostomy tube placement for prolonged respiratory failure and neurologic compromise.  The patient had uneventful ventilatory requirements and ultimately was performing intermittent spontaneous breathing trials; however, still had episodes of apnea, but improved.  He was tolerating tube feeds at goal with resolution of his small bowel obstruction, which was thought secondary to his Guillain-Barre.  The patient did develop abnormal LFTs which were thought secondary to cholecystitis not requiring operative intervention, with improving LFT findings on antibiotics.  The patient had a nonobstructive cholecystitis.  The patient's mentation was improving to the point where he was able to communicate and open his eyes upon discharge, as well as was working with Physical Therapy for strengthening.  He was able to move his upper extremities and followed commands and lower extremities were improving in strength as well. Patient was discharged via private air flight to acute care ICU facility.
LAB_DATA: 3/20/21 Hgb  15.2 Hct 45 platelets 134,000.  3/24/21 Hemoglobin 13.2, hematocrit 39.9, white blood cell count 6.9, platelets 153,000.  RADIOGRAPHIC STUDIES:   MRI scan of the brain on 03/20/2021: No diffusion restriction has developed in the interval to suggest acute infarct. No new abnormalities otherwise noted. MRI of the brain without contrast on 03/19/2021, "No acute intracranial abnormality.  No acute infarct.  Chronic mild cerebral volume loss and white matter microangiopathic changes." CT angiogram of the head and the neck on 03/19/2021: No acute intracranial abnormality.  Major proximal intracranial arteries are patent without stenosis, aneurysm or vascular malformation.  Neck carotid and vertebral arteries are normal.  No atherosclerotic disease or stenosis.

I got itchy bumps all over. I thought it was a mosquito or bed bugs because I never had a reaction to any vaccine before this (and I have had a lot of vaccines - even smallpox years ago for a lab job), but my husband didn't get a single bite (we do everything together - work in same office, share same bed, etc). Then it went away after 2-3 weeks, so I wrote it off. Then I got my second dose of Moderna on 03/22/2021, and the rash started again but less severe this time. He still never had any symptoms, and we hadn't gone anywhere besides work/home. That's when I realized that it was probably related to the vaccine. I don't plan to go to the doctor for it since it went away the first time & it's almost gone now - only a 2-3 itchy places left.  Each place was like a tiny blister on a mosquito bite. I popped one and it was filled with clear liquid. I wish the lady giving me the shot had warned me about this.  I went on a cleaning rampage after I felt better the first time - cause I was worried it was some kind of bug & I was really worried.  Also, I think maybe this won't be reported often cause people might think it's just something else like I did.

32-year-old otherwise healthy woman presents to the emergency department with increasing fatigue and palpitations with tachycardia. Today (4/13/21) the patient had fatigue and progressive weakness with palpitations with exertion walking up the stairs.  She presented with tachycardia, her heart rate of 130, BP 140/79, she is afebrile with 100% pulse ox on room air.  She has no evidence of exudative pharyngitis or oropharyngeal allergic reaction.  No signs of meningitis.  She has no evidence of pneumonia.  No abdominal tenderness.  She does have some nausea.  She denies any urinary frequency urgency.  No abnormal vaginal discharge.  No other rashes.  COVID test negative. Patient admitted for observation

White count of 13,000 hemoglobin of 12.4, MCV of 79.3, prominent monocytes normal platelets, basic metabolic panel shows a potassium of 3.2, normal renal function with an anion gap of 18.  Point-of-care lactate was three-point with a pH of 7.45 and a bicarb of 19.9.  D-dimer was 233, ruling out pulmonary embolism.  Urinalysis is negative for infection.  She is not pregnant.  MD recognize clinical syndrome of sepsis with elevated white count, tachycardia in the lactic acid 3.89.  She meets criteria for sepsis with shock but without organ failure.  PA and lateral chest x-ray showed no pneumonia.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Provider's Notes for 4-10-2021 visit:  29 y/o F presents to Urgent Care with c/o possible side effects after receiving 1st dose of Pfizer BioNtech COVID-19 vaccine yesterday evening. Reports to feeling pruritis in R arm at time of vaccine administration but this resolved within few minutes. However, pt admits to waking up with headache and R sided body pain. Husband noted erythematous rash behind pt's ear; pt denies warmth, pruritis or tenderness at rash site. Symptoms of generalized body aches and chills have developed in the last few hours (similar to symptoms of cold). Took excedrin with relief to headache and myalgias.   Denies recent use of antihistamine but adds that she was prescribed cetirizine and diphenhydramine by PCP for hx of random rashes that occur after being outdoors. Pt also states that she was recently prescribed cyclobenzaprine, meloxicam and norco for R "trapezius" pain. She was referred to physical therapy by specialist recently. Last use of pain medication was 1 week ago.   Denies arthralgias, numbness, tingling, rash or pruritis at injection site (does have soreness), fever, sore throat, dysphagia, facial/neck swelling, chest pain, SOB, nausea, vomiting, diarrhea, inner or external ear pain, discharge from ear, rhinorrhea, post nasal drip, persisting headache, hx of anaphylactic reaction to meds or vaccine in past.   Adverse reaction to vaccine product Due to acute onset of symptoms after recent vaccine administration (onset within 12hrs), pt's symptoms of myalgias, acute onset rash, chills are likely mild adverse reaction to the recent COVID-19 vaccine. No current signs of anaphylaxis and pt was reassured. She opted to take cetirizine while at clinic. PO or IM steroids will be avoided to reduce risk of suppressing intended immune response to vaccine. May apply topical hydrocortisone or topical benadryl if rash becomes pruritic. RTC if symptoms worsen or persist. ER precautions discussed for acute worsening. Pt and her husband voiced understanding.   Start cetirizine 10 mg tablet 1 tablet as needed  On examination - erythematous rash See above recs. Cellulitis is low in ddx due to acute onset of symptoms, bilateral distribution, and lack of tenderness. Monitor closely.   Muscle pain Can continue acetaminophen or NSAIDs with food as needed. RTC if symptoms worsen or persist.
OTHER_MEDS: Cetirizine 10 mg tablet - Take 1 tablet as needed by oral route; Cyclobenzaprine PRN; Excedrin PRN for headache; HYDROcodone-acetaminophen PRN; Meloxicam PRN

SYMPTOM_TEXT: The patient had a needle phobia and was very anxious prior to the vaccine. Once the patient received the vaccine, he waited in the waiting area for 15 minutes post-vaccine. About 5 minutes after the vaccine, he notified the pharmacy staff that he wasn't feeling well and he was feeling faint. The pharmacy staff provided him with a glass of water and was monitoring him. He said he  felt like he fainted and wasn't feeling well. He said he felt warm and sweaty. The pharmacy staff provided him with an ice pack. He then notified the pharmacy staff that he urinated in his chair while waiting post-vaccine. He wanted to be checked out and wanted us to call 911 . The patient began to feel better after about 20 minutes. The EMT arrived and checked the patient. Even though, the patient was feeling better, the EMT recommended the patient be checked further anyways. He was brought to the Triage center and was there for about 1 hour, according to the patient, and was feeling better. He said he felt slightly fatigued that day and the following day, but other than that he was feeling back to normal and no issues. He stated he has severe needle phobia and has experienced these fainting spells and anxiousness in the past. We followed up with the patient and he provided this information to us. He stated he was feeling good and back to normal. He had no further questions or concerns. We told him to follow up with us if questions or concerns came up.
PRIOR_VAX: needle phobias, has experienced fainting and feeling anxious and unwell from prior vaccines

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Per patient he received his second Covid vaccine 3 days prior to arrival and immediately following developed myalgias, subjective fevers and " viral symptoms" which she managed with ibuprofen 2 tabs q6h some improvement.  On the day prior to arrival he developed increasing shortness of breath particularly with talking and with ambulation.  He also describes chest tightness with deep inspiration, the tightness radiates to back, no radiation to left arm or jaw.  Chest tightness is non-positional, but does feel worse immediately after he lies down from ambulation and then slowly dissipates.  His last subjective fever was yesterday evening.  He has never had a reaction to the vaccine before.  He has no allergies.  No prior medical conditions he is aware of, and takes no medications.  He did not experience any of the symptoms following the first vaccine. He has h/o asymptomatic COVID infection in November 2020. Cardiology consulted for concern of pericarditis post COVID-19 vaccine. He does not have significant ST elevation or PR depression.  He also does not have evidence of significant pericardial effusion at this point.  The high sensitivity troponins are mildly elevated.  He does have viral syndrome.  Is unclear if Covid vaccination was causally related to his symptoms.  We would like to improve his medications for better chest pain control and to prevent recurrent pericarditis in the future.
LAB_DATA: He presented to emergency department on day of admission.  In the ED, he was found to have mild leukocytosis 11.2 with otherwise normal CBC and BMP, a troponin elevation to 0.23, EKG with mild ST elevations in V2 through V4 (most likely early repolarization, not meeting criteria for STEMI) negative D-dimer, negative Covid, influenza, RSV and chest x-ray without acute cardiopulmonary abnormality.

Immediately following injection (within 15 minutes) arm pain and numbness/tingling to fingers, slight nausea and dizziness. Lasted approximately 4 hours. Extreme dizziness for approximately 2-3 minutes while sitting still at 4 hour mark - resolved with rest except arm pain, which lessened slightly over the first hour but remained unresolved after 4 hours.  Within 30 minutes post injection - redness, heat, and swelling at injection site.   After injection (approximately 12-13 hours post injection) - Fever (100-101.7 consistently over 3 days), extreme fatigue, headache, muscle aches/joint pain, severe chills. Fever broke midday April 4, and other symptoms except arm pain and headaches slowly resolved by April 7. Arm pain remained at a fairly steady level throughout that time and past April 8 (one week).  Currently (April 14, two weeks post injection) - arm pain has lessened, but remains in upper arm. Particularly sensitive to touch or movement, but can be felt at rest. Redness is gone, but palpable hard lump and heat remain at injection site. Pain and sensitivity noted when medical provider palpated underarm lymph nodes on right side. Not noted in same action under left arm. Headaches continue intermittently.

I had a severely inflamed optic nerve in the R eye and my L eye optic nerve was inflamed but not to the extent of the Right one.  I was sent to get an echo cardiogram and a carotid artery ultrasound.  I was referred to a neurologist ophthalmologist but couldn't get in until March 12. Patient reports h/o hypothyroidism, depression, migraines, and duodenitis. She takes Synthroid QD, Effexor QD, Sumatriptan PRN, and unspecified antacid or PPI PRN (no flares > 6 months). CV: RRR, no m/r/g PULM: Clear to auscultation bilaterally, no accessory muscle use ABD: deferred SKIN: vaccine site at left deltoid without edema, erythema, bleeding, or discharge. SYMPTOM_TEXT: The patient is a 58 y.o. female who presents to the Emergency Department with abdominal pain, vomiting, and fever at 101 degrees that began two days ago. She reports additional c/o diarrhea and bilateral flank pain.
LAB_DATA: CT scan of the abdomen confirms no sign of diverticulitis or inflammatory bowel changes. Results are overall reassuring. I went and reassessed the patient. The patient was informed that this may be an early presentation of a more serious disease and that close follow up is absolutely mandatory. Patient understands this. At this point, the patient has been able to tolerate PO. Reexamination of her abdomen reveals a soft, non tender abdomen with no acute surgical processes identified. Given these reassuring findings, we will proceed with discharge home. Pt is comfortable with this plan. Prescriptions for Zofran and Norco have been written so that she can continue to treat any continual symptoms at home. Return precautions for any new, worsening or other concerning symptom were discussed at this time. Patient has verbalized understanding. They will be discharged home.

Patient came in and got his shingles shot on 01/30/2021. When patient came in, techncian put in shingles shot, and gave patient consent form to fill out. Patient answered no to every question on the consent form and did not have a fever. The vaccine was administered. After the vaccine was given the patient asked what he could get over the counter for shingles, indicating after the shot was givenf that he had an active shingles rash. However, the vaccine was not a live vaccine, the pharamcist verified the dose was still valid and patient had doctors appointment next day for shingles rash the next day.   The next day he received treatment for his singles and let the doctor know he received the vaccine while he had the rash. Patient called pharmacy several months later in early April indicating that his shingles had still not gone away, and that he had a very severe case. He was admitted to the ER on March 27th, due to severe rash on his chest that was cauing chest pain. They did ECG, first came back abnormal, but second came back normal.  Patient is now at home stating that he is starting to feel better, but feels as though this reaction was due to getting Shingrix shot with the shingles.  I called the CDC and the CDC verifed that "The adverse reactions form the Shingrix shot and symptoms of the disease can occur at the same time, but we would not expect a combined effect" The shot would not exacerbate the shingles disease or make it worse".  The patient just wanted this reaction documented as to provide information and further research.

The day after receiving the vaccine, I experienced common side effects of fever, chills, body aches, and nausea, which lasted for 24 hours, and then I felt better. Then, 3 days after receiving the vaccine, I suddenly began to have extreme stomach pain, so bad that I could barely walk or stand up straight. My chest felt tight and I had shortness of breath. I thought about going to the ER, but called my GI specialist instead as I thought it could be related to the Xifaxan I was taking, but the office was already closed. The GI office called the following Monday and said the Xifaxan should not cause extreme stomach pain and to go to the ER if it persists, but by this time I was feeling much better. The severe pain lasted two days in total.

i received the vaccine at 3pm on monday april 12th. i started shaking less than 5 minutes after i received the dose and my throat started to swell and i couldn?t swallow. they placed me under observation for 30 minutes and gave me water?saying that ?i might just be afraid of the needle and not to worry, this is an abnormally normal reaction to a new vaccine.? after 30 minutes a man walked over to me and said ?oh you?re still here?? and chuckled. they then told me i would be fine after a while and to leave. i started walking down the sidewalk and almost passed out so i called an uber to take me to the nearest urgent care. i arrived at urgent care around 4pm unable to swallow and having a reaction to the vaccine. they saw me immediately and gave me 3 50mg of prednisone and a benadryl and placed me under observation for 45 minutes. he said i looked better and i even felt marginally better. i called another uber and when i was almost home my tongue started to go numb as well as my lips and my breathing was becoming constricted. i had the uber driver pull over as i had to sit on the sidewalk and get some air. i then called another uber to the hospital because my symptoms were becoming increasingly more alarming. Hospital admitted me and gave me a shot of epinephrine and IV fluids and kept me under observation for 6 hours. they discharged me a little after midnight with a prescription for prednisone, epinephrine, and benadryl. if i had been administered epinephrine at the vaccine site on monday and not been told i was just squeamish by the male air force cadets?i probably wouldn?t still be short of breath, painfully swallowing, and bedridden.
CUR_ILL: tested pos for covid-19 on february 25th and tested negative  on march 31st.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: About an hour afterwards I could taste it. Whenever I get IVs I can taste and smell them. I did not expect the same reaction from an intramuscular shot, but I suppose once it got into my bloodstream and got to my olfactory areas, it started up. It really does produce the same taste as when I get an IV. For the past four days since I've gotten the shot, about once a day I get this same taste and smell. It happened again today a few minutes ago, so I thought I would report that after four days as it's going through my system and is still detectable physically. In addition, last night on 4/13/2021, I was a little congested, so I coughed hard to bring up some phlegm. There were two small spots of blood in the phlegm. I coughed five times and had the same amount of blood. I waited a few minutes and coughed again, and it turned into a pink-tinged mucus. Then it cleared up and it hasn't happened again. It was very tiny and I can't say it was from the vaccine, because nothing else has happened. It could be my age and thin tissue and a broken vein from a very deep cough, but yeah. it was very scary and I thought I would report it in case something more happens.
OTHER_MEDS: Valium, vitamin D, Vitamin C, Elderberry and Zinc, multivitamin

SYMPTOM_TEXT: On the same day I received both the first and second shots, while resting, my watch alerted me to the fact my heart rate had gone up to 135+.   I have had occasional bouts with tachycardia before but rarely.  Maybe 5 or 6 times in  the last year, but those times my heart rate returned to normal quickly.  My Dr. was not aware of this issue, I had planned to talk to her about it when I have my annual physical since it was happening so rarely.  I actually didn't even have a name for it until it happened after my first Covid shot, because at that time and when it happened after the 2nd shot, my heart did not return to it's normal rate (mid 60's) for at least 15 minutes and I was more concerned.
LAB_DATA: I contacted my physician, and an EKG was ordered, which was done on 2/15/21.  This is when I was diagnosed with tachycardia.   I was also scheduled to wear a heart monitor for 2 weeks, and am scheduled to see a cardiologist on Monday, April 26th.  While I was wearing the heart monitor, I received my 2nd shot (3/9/2021) and had the second incident with high heart rate.  So, while I apparently had the condition of tachycardia, I believe the Moderna shot caused me to have a heart rate incident each time I received a dose, and the incident lasted longer than ever before.  I've not had an incident since receiving the second shot on March 9, 2021

The patient is a 66 y.o. female with past history of diabetes, GERD and HTN who presents to the Emergency Department with visual changes of the right eye and associated pain to the face and neck. Per interpretor, patient woke up feeling at baseline yesterday morning, when she had her COVID-19 vaccine. Yesterday around dinner time, she began having issues with vision in her right eye, causing her visual field in that eye to appear dark to her entire right eye. She told her husband that she thought she might have a hair or eyelash in her right eye and that she had an irritating pain radiating from her right eye to the right side of her face. Even after washing her eye with cold water, the sensation did not subside. At approximately 3-4 AM this morning, she also began to experience pain to the back of her head and neck bilaterally. This morning, the visual impairment improved from the entire visual field to now only just the inferior aspect of the right eye. However, she denies weakness to any of her extremities. Patient also denies chest pain, numbness, abdominal pain or nausea. She was seen at ophthalmology, at which Dr. diagnosed her with a right retinal branch arterial occlusion and decided to send her to SHE to be evaluated for the possibility of a CVA. She denies being on blood thinners or taking Aspirin. She denies any previous diagnosis of a CVA or TIA.
LAB_DATA: The patient is a 66 y.o. female evaluated for visual impairment of the right eye and associated pain to the head and neck. Today, patient is noted to have mild tenderness to the bilateral neck posteriorly and right sided headache. However, she has a normal neurologic exam. She has no history of CVA or TIA. Ddx includes, but is not limited to: CVA, TIA, carotid or vertebral artery dissection, and carotid artery occlusion. Full ophthalmic exam was already performed at her ophthalmologist appointment so I did not focus on that portion of the exam, but will instead evaluate for causes of artery occlusion in the right eye. Will proceed with obtainment of labs, CT imaging and MRI of the brain.

I received the vaccine at 3:50 pm and by 9:45 I had the typical side effects --muscle aches, minor pain at the injection site, and chills.  Within an hour from that I also had a terrible headache, nausea, and my skin hurt to touch.  I slept most of the next day, save for 5 or 6 hours.  Starting on 3/30/21 (exactly two weeks from receiving my vaccine) I started having sore skin.  No rash, red marks, itching, just hypersensitive to touch, even with clothing.  This started on my right arm right above the elbow.  The following day the pain had moved to inside both arms right above the elbow.  The day after that, the pain was more intense and was straight across my stomach at belly button height, and across my lower back at that same height.  It was more intense for two days and hurt whether anything was touching my skin or not.  It was very uncomfortable.  In the days following it continued to move to different places on my body.  Legs, bottom of feet, palms of hands, ankles, hips, groin, lower back.    Sometimes it just hurts, sometimes it's like a prickling, sometimes the skin in that area aches -- especially when on my hands. It's also very sensitive to anything cold.  Again, if you look at my skin though you can't see anything.  There's no visible signs of something being wrong.  It also stopped for a day or so, or just lessened so much that it wasn't that noticeable, but then returns.  That's happened twice where I thought this was finally over, only to have it return the next day.
LAB_DATA: I did not pursue medical testing as since there's no visible reaction like a rash or red irritated skin I wasn't sure what they can really do for me.
OTHER_MEDS: Women's multi-vitamin, genius burn thermogenic, Claritin
ALLERGIES: Allergic to sulfa drugs Suspected seasonal allergies, but never been tested for that - manage the allergies with Claritin

LAB_DATA: Patient has a negative UA. Her XR is also negative for bowel obstruction. There is a moderate diffuse stool burden but no other acute findings.  The patient states that she is feeling significantly improved and asymptomatic. I informed her of her findings. Patient feels reassured at this time. We discussed that she will need outpatient follow up with her PCP and she will plan to schedule an appointment in the next coupe of days. She also tells me that she is not compliant on her diabetic and anti hypertensive medication but that she does have it at home. I emphasized the importance of taking this medication. She understands this. Due to the stool burden found on x-ray I am giving her a stool softener to aid in this. Patient is comfortable with this plan. Return precautions for any new, worsening or other concerning symptom were discussed at this time. Patient has verbalized understanding. They will be discharged home.   Impression:   1. Medics noted that she was orthostatic on the scene as well.   She currently is feeling well, has no complaints.  States that she has gotten dizzy before in the past with COVID vaccines.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient received his J&J vaccine for COVID-19 on 03/10/2021.  On 3/17, he was at the grocery store when he felt a sting on his left lateral ankle. When he pulled up his pant leg, he saw the small little red spots that were exquisitely tender. He went immediately to his primary care physician's office, where he was prescribed Bactrim for suspected cellulitis. The rash steadily worsened with extension up his left leg and onto his right leg and blistering of some of the lesions most markedly in his groin. Pain associated with the rash increased and remained most severe on the lateral aspect of the left ankle. He presented back to his primary care physician's office on 3/19, where he was given methylprednisolone 80 milligrams IV, discharged with a prescription for prednisone 60 milligrams daily for the next few days. Pain worsened the morning of 3/20/21 to the point that he was unable to bear much weight on the left leg prompting his presentation to the emergency department.
LAB_DATA: In the emergency department, vitals were notable for being afebrile, heart rate 111, blood pressure 162/104, normal oxygen saturation on room air. He was noted to have a maculopapular rash on bilateral lower extremities extending up the trunk to the chest.  Laboratory workup showed a normal CBC, creatinine 1.29 (baseline 1), AST 34, ALT 36, alk-phos 117. INR was 2.3 on warfarin.  For pain, he was given 1 tab of Norco and morphine 4 milligrams IV. He was admitted to General Medicine for further management.   The patient was afebrile. He denied any chills, night sweats, change in weight, myalgias, arthralgias, or genitourinary, gastrointestinal, or pulmonary symptoms. The only medication he took was warfarin, and he denied any new or changes in supplements or medications. The patient denied history of autoimmune disease or recent infections. He was up to date on age-appropriate cancer screenings. Connective tissue and autoimmune laboratory work-up was negative, including antinuclear antibody, anti-double stranded DNA, perinuclear and cytoplasmic antineutrophil cytoplasmic antibodies, rheumatoid factor, extractable nuclear antigen panel, and compliment C3 and C4 level testing were within normal limits. Hepatitis panel and HIV antigen antibody testing were non-reactive. Hematologic, renal, and hepatic function were within normal limits. Direct immunofluorescence microscopy of a biopsied specimen from a new lesion on the abdomen was negative for specific immune deposits. Biopsy from his thigh revealed fibrinoid necrosis of vessel walls with fibrin thrombi, extravasated erythrocytes, and neutrophilic inflammatory infiltrate with leukocytoclasia. SARS COV-2 in situ hybridization was negative. The diagnosis of LCV was rendered, and initiation of high dose corticosteroids led to improvement of his cutaneous symptoms and clinical appearance of the rash. He was discharged with a home taper prednisone plan to complete 5 day course of each as follows: 100 mg, 80 mg, 60 mg, 40 mg, 20 mg, and 10 mg.    The patient also presented with severe left ankle pain. The ankle lesions preceded the ankle pain, so it was suspected that the pain was likely related to cutaneous vasculitis. Ankle XR was not concerning for acute process, only soft tissue swelling.  ESR and CRP were 40 and 1.7 respectively.  He was afebrile, had a normal white blood cell count, and denied systemic symptoms.  His physical exam was not concerning for septic arthritis.  Vascular etiologies were ruled out with duplex and doppler of the left lower extremity. While inpatient, the patient's pain was managed with scheduled Tylenol and low-dose opiates as needed.  The patient was provided with a walker to take home with him.  He was also provided a short course of opiate pain medication.  The risks and benefits of taking the medication were discussed with the patient and start talking form was completed. Outpatient follow up with dermatology on 3/24/2021 showed continued improvement of the lesions, and no new lesions. However, left ankle pain was still prominent. Phone call on 4/14/2021 the patient reported continued difficulty with walking and oozing of the lesions.
CUR_ILL: was treated for acute recurrent sinusitis; URI: 2/24/2021 was treated with amoxicillin
HISTORY: Left proximal DVT on chronic anticoagulation, depression/anxiety, OSA, Erectile dysfunction w inflatable penile, prosthesis replaced 10/2020
ALLERGIES: no known allergies to medications or otherwise

I had a headache the next morning but no other symptoms initially.  Then, Saturday evening, just over 24 hours after receiving the J&J vaccine I was sitting in landscape pavers outside in jeans and a long sleeve shirt next to the pool. My husband looked over and said what is wrong with your feet, they are blue. He said that is not good with circulation and you should probably talk to your doctor. Unfortunately I did not take a picture at the time and noted I was a little chilly but would reach out to my doctor if it continued and didn?t think anything more of it until I saw the reports Tuesday morning of them recommending to stop the J&J vaccine.   I called my doctors office Tuesday morning and they asked me to come in over lunch to see the doctor. While sitting waiting to see the doctor my feel replicated the situation from Saturday  night. My toes were especially blue up through my ankle and the doctor pointed out I had red patches looking like a rash. She also noticed my right leg was worse and more swollen up to just below my knee. We did take pictures that we can share if prompted.

Lightheadedness and exhaustion set in 15-25 minutes post injection. Later that same evening, experienced nausea, muscle, bone, and joint aches as well as chest pain that were much reduced by the following morning. Malaise continued as did symptoms of nausea without vomiting.  24 hours post injection, experienced a low grade fever of 99.6 F (for me, this is a low grade temp). Fever broke after another 24 hours.  Experienced severe headaches in the middle of the forehead for 8-12 hours on 3/25/2021, 3/29/2021, 4/3/2021.  Experienced difficulty breathing 3/30/2021. Woke up from deep sleep feeling starved for oxygen and a sensation that a deep enough breath could not be taken--the lungs could  not expand enough. Respiratory rate seemed slightly depressed. It passed after about 30 minutes with focused effort on taking deep, regular breaths. Fell asleep again and did not consult a medical provider about it. The oxygen hunger / breathing issue did not repeat.  Medical professionals were not consulted for any of the episodes described above.

After 5 mins of getting the 1st shot I felt an allergic reaction little bit hard to breathe and hot flash.  I told the pharmacist and was advised to stay an extra 10 minutes.  I left the Pharmacy and proceeded to the store and then home.  Over the next 1.5 days I felt a sort of brain fog, my arm puffed up red about the size of a half dollar.  The brain fog went away and then for the next 2-3 days  my body felt like I was coming down with a cold.  I seemed to feel better after that initial period until 3/24 when while driving a hot flash came over me and the next day I was again in a type of brain fog.  For the next two days I tried to just deal with the brain fog but started to notice on the right side of my neck a feeling of constriction, with abnormally high blood pressure.  I went to the hospital ER and the completed a CAT scan of my brain and neck, blood work and urine work up with no evidence of why my neck was feeling constricted and high blood pressure.  The symptoms continued and on 4/1 my blood pressure  spike to 168/93 and I again went back to the hospital ER and spent the night.  I was having heart palpitations, anxiety and very high blood pressure.  The hospital this time completed more bloodwork, MRI of my brain and neck and an Eco-cardiogram.  I am now on 3 blood pressure and heart medications and have no diagnoses of why my blood pressure and heart rate are so abnormal.  I am very healthy and exercise daily and have never encountered this and my BP has always been extremely good.
LAB_DATA: CAT scan brain and neck 3/27 Full blood work 3/27 MRI head and neck  4/1 Eco-cardiogram 4/1 EKG 4/1
OTHER_MEDS: Rosuvastatin 20 mg daily and Bayer low dose 81 mg daily

LAB_DATA: 3:54 PM - Chest XR appears like severe COPD. No obvious acute infiltrate.   5:34 PM - Procalcitonin is slightly elevated but labs are otherwise normal. COVID test is negative. She is on 3.5 liters of oxygen and sats are at 95%. She has been having purulent sputum. We will treat with antibiotics. I will send him home with a prescription for Adoxa and Deltasone. I advised her to follow up with her PCP for further evaluation. Strict return precautions were given prior to discharge.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Developed "moderna arm" (raised inflammation with itching 1.5-2 inches long and 0.5-1 inches across) 7 days post vaccination from injection 1.   Developed somewhat severe tension headache on day 1 post vaccination from injection 2 (all further events listed below are from injection 2). Headache responded to ibuprofen.  On day 4 post vaccination, began experiencing minor and infrequent migraine-like headaches that lasted for a few seconds to a minute. Moderate pain and localized. Pain site changed but was generally on left side. Experienced 0-2 a day until day 12.  On day 11 post vaccination, began experiencing full, moderate tension headache. In addition, had more frequent migraine-like headaches. Did not respond to 400mg ibuprofen or 10mg Claritin.  On day 12 post vaccination, began experiencing photophobia. Mentioned to general practitioner out of an abundance of caution who recommended Excedrin. Took two Excedrin extra strength (total dosage: Acetomenaphin 500mg, Aspirin 500 mg, Caffeine 130 mg). Tension headache ended and most (but not all) migraine-like pain subsided. Some occasional pain ranging from 1-2 out of 10.  On day 13 out of an abundance of caution following reports of other events I went to the ER. The doctor there examined for any cognitive symptoms (asked me to follow her finger with my eyes, squeeze fingers, checked ability to move extremities, etc) and concluded no risk of CVST. Determined that vaccine likely lowered my threshold for headaches and migraines (I have had very infrequent cluster headaches lasting for a few seconds in the past, never for this duration). Final diagnosis was migraines. Doctor prescribed Fioricet and gave me a long-acting steroid. Some pain is still there, but symptoms have mostly stopped. Waves of quick bursts of pain on localized areas on the left side of my head are still occuring.
LAB_DATA: Doctor performed exam to rule out CVST. Asked me to follow finger with eyes, touch nose and then touch her finger, checked movement in extremities, etc. Determined no reason to suspect CVST.
OTHER_MEDS: Vyvanse 20mg Men's multivitamin Claritin 10mg for allergies

I received the vaccine at approx 930 am, Wed, March 17 (Johnson and Johnson Lot 1805020) at the Facility by Fireman(Emergency Responders). Vaccine was from Health Care. At first, after about 15 minutes I was feeling a little flush, there were light red splotches on my skin (only a couple, very light red - like when i get really nervous and get red splotches on my neck.) I felt a little nauseous and dizzy off an on for about an hour (but i had not had anything to eat or drink yet that day either). The site of the shot was a little sore and warm about an inch or two away from the needle injection site, but not a big deal. That night my right arm (which is where i received the shot) ached terribly, all the way from my shoulder to my fingers. The next day (Thursday, March 18) was the same. Sometimes my left arm tingled like it was starting to fall asleep. This went on the whole next day. Injection site still sore too, and warm.  The day after that (Friday, March 19) the injection site was sore (like a sore muscle) and that was it. Saturday, March 20, the same until about midnight. Around midnight my son, and I came upstairs from watching tv and my arm (at my wrist) was aching intensly! I looked down and there was a small lump where one if the veins are. I can see my veins easily here and I am very light-skinned. Son could also see the lump. My arm kept aching so badly! I was messaging the lump over and over. After about 5-10 minutes it went down a little bit, ached a little less, and i left it alone. The next day it looked like i had a bruise on my wrist and hand (where the meaty part of your hand is  going to the thumb. The next day, Sunday, March 20th, a neighbor said it could be a blood clot and i took an aspirin.    Today, Wednesday, April 14, 2021.   Approx 1130am, after getting out of bed, getting some coffee. I was sitting at my desk in my home office, took my medication and took my first sip of coffee. All of a sudden, my chest starting hurting. I cant say where the pain originated, it was in the chest/upper stomach area. It ached a lot, I felt very flush, I honestly cant remember if it were hard to breath, all i could think is "what is this?". I didn't know if i would throw up, burp, pass out. the aches starting migrating, still saying in the chest, but expanding to my lower back. I got out of my chair and tried to move around...it took a good 3-5 minutes before it started to dissipate and I took another aspirin.
vomiting, shortness of breath, hospitalized, chart shows she suffered from blood clot, hospital has extensive records from tests
LAB_DATA: many, contact  for records from hospitalization March 27-April 1

My heart kept pounding harder and faster and didn't come down. My watch said tit started going up to:  122 to 144  to 154 and it kept gradually going up. I was petting the dog and sitting in the recliner. I phone my Dr's on-call number and spoke to him on the phone. I called 9-1-1 by his advice. Paramedics came - Heartrate stayed up.  I was still able to walk around the house. I followed up to their truck and they checked me over. By that time as they were taking my vitals my heart rate started to calm down.  (It was elevated about 15 minutes about all together) My blood pressure - 160 over 110 when the paramedics checked me but that was coming down as they had me at the truck and the heart rate went down to 80-90 and was continuing to go down. It hasn't come back.  They listened to my heart. Never had that happen to me before like that. Didn't have to go to ER. I do have the apple records of my heart rate, etc. if needed. The joint pain and fatigue faded back to my baseline.

Diagnosis was dehydration likely caused by menstruating at same time as vaccination. Prescribed nsaid and muscle relaxer to reduce symptoms and action plan for increasing water and natural iron intake prior to next dose to prevent more dangerous complications. Had hospitalization for SARS in 2009 and also treated for dehydration, did not consider the vaccine might have a similar effect to the prior infection since I was coughing so hard I was vomiting up all water for 3 days, but my vaccine symptoms were VERY similar to the 2009 illness in slow mo without the coughing including the pain and nausea (hospital could only confirm it was an unknown coronavirus at the time my roommate brought from another county, he was a another race native and very ill but was not hospitalized and didn?t disclose he was sick so he wouldn?t miss the start of the semester in quarantine, flew anyway and didn?t tell us until I was hospitalized). Still dehydrated at 2 weeks after vaccine (today) but functionally symptom free at this time. Menstruation was normal, lighter flow than usual, and lasted 7 days which is normal for me post-IUD. Symptoms persisted after period stopped but progressively improved thereafter, unclear if because of home care for potential clot or because no longer menstruating so better able to retain water.

On March 4 patient experienced vomiting. Early morning March 5 he fell and landed on his hip after being disoriented and experienced aches, weakness, and nausea without vomiting throughout the day. On March 6 he experienced excruciating pain in his left hip and went to the local emergency room following guidance from his primary care physician. He was diagnosed with fluid near his hip joint at the hospital and was discharged the same day. The next day, March 7 he was still in pain but able to walk with assistance. On March 8 he got an x-ray from an orthopedic physician and severe arthritis was found. March 10 the severe pain persisted, but he was able to walk with a walker. On March 12 he received a cortisone shot and required emergency medical assistance to get into a personal vehicle with a family member who drove to the appointment. The next few days, the pain persisted, became worse, and spread throughout his body. On March 16 he was transported by emergency medical services to the local emergency room for treatment and was diagnosed with sepsis and pneumonia. On March 18 he was still being treated when he experienced cardiac arrest while being intubated. He was resuscitated and was on a ventilator being treated for a few more days but ultimately succumbed to sepsis on March 30.
LAB_DATA: March 8 - Severe arthritis March 16 - Sepsis and Pneumonia

He said, " I blinked, fell to the ground and next he saw people standing around him."  He said, no nausea, just lightheaded and he hit the side of his head lightly. Staff helped him into a wheelchair and took him to the office.  I spoke with him in the office and asked him if he wanted to go to the hospital.  I received this information from the patient when I asked him if he could tell me what happened.  He was sweating and pale, but no nausea, no disturbance in his vision and his blood pressure wasn't elevated.   He told me again that he took no regular medication,  but a couple of years ago he had been dizzy after a tetanus shot.  I asked again if he had any discomfort or pain anywhere and he said only his arm felt sore near the shot.   I asked again if he felt like he would like to go to the hospital and he said no.  His family came and picked him up.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 7 PM (4.5 hours after J & J shot) - Chills begin, both calf muscle in legs starting to shake. I move to my bed. 7:30 PM - In bed, dressed in sweatshirt, wool socks, etc., a a couple blankets wrapped around me, space heater turned to 80 degrees, shaking uncontrollably from being so cold (mostly hands and feet), mild headache begins in middle back of head.  8:00 PM - still freezing, temperature was at 98.7. most of body is aching 9:00 PM - chills and body ache starting to slow down, temperature at 100.3 9:30 PM - still have chills, space heater still on and i was still wrapped in a bunch of clothing/blankets. temp at 100.5 and i drank 6 oz water.  10 PM - chills going away, heat/blankets/clothing still on, temp at 101. body aches mostly only in left and right calf.   Rest of night until around 4 A.M. was me tossing and turning being restless. My heart rate was ~130 BPM throughout the entire night according to my smart watch. I was checking my temperature constantly with an infrared thermometer and it was between 101-102.5. I probably drank ~24 oz of water throughout the night. It felt like each time i fell asleep, i would wake up no more than 30 min later and each time i woke up it felt like i had been asleep for 5 hours. At a few moments it felt like i was hallucinating seeing little boxes around my head.. At no point  during the episode did i take any advil/tyenol/etc. Only drank water. Woke up around noon the next day, I felt extremely groggy, still had a headache and my temperature was back to ~98.  I ate for the first time that day around 1 P.M. and had a few advil which helped with my headache.

4 days after vaccination pt experienced severe abdominal pain the RLQ and diarrhea.  Pt was sent from village to emergency room where i evaluated, exam with significant RLQ tenderness but no rebound or guarding, some LLQ tenderness as well.   With exception of mild tachycardia and slight hypertension associated with pain, vitals were normal.
LAB_DATA: WBC was normal 6.18k/uL, with slight monocytosis 1.24(20%) and 32 bands present. CRP was elevated at 4.89mg/dL.  This led to CT which revealed significant inflammation of the distal jejunum without appendicitis, no abscess, and no other infectious suggestions.  Covid was negative same day, a DNA GI panel covering campylobacter, Cdiff, plesiomonas, salmonella, vibrio, yersinia enterocolitica, EAEC, EPEC, ETEC, STEC, EIEC, cryptosporidium, cyclospora, entamoeba, giardia, adenovirus, astrovirus, norovirus, rotavirus, was negative. The patient reported no history of colitis or similar symptoms, reported no family history of autoimmune disease.  Pt was considered for admission but was watched closely via multiple ED and outpatient visits during her recovery.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I submitted a report after my first dose of the vaccine , and now this is the report after my 2nd dose of the Pfizer vaccine: I got the 2nd dose at 4:10pm. I did not feel the shot at all this time, but my arm was a bit achy soon after. One hour after the shot my leg muscles hurt and I felt fatigued. Two hours after the shot I felt really tired and really silly, kind of loopy. Three hours after the shot my L arm was hurting more and it hurt to take the band aid off. Then my stomach started feeling upset. I went to bed at 10:30pm and had a very rough sick night. I was awake most of the night, only dozing a few times. I had a fever (101) and chills; nausea and belching; dry mouth; aching and strange pains coming and going; a slight headache; and my L arm was hurting. By 7am I started crying, and I had more physical pain.  I got up at 8am feeling so sick with extreme fatigue, headache, and in a lot of pain in body. My Mom had to make my breakfast for me and I took small bites of that oatmeal throughout the day. I couldn't eat very much because my stomach was so upset. I felt hot and cold and got chills often during the day. By 6:45pm the fever returned (100.3) and I felt sicker again with head and tummy hurting; body aching; and nausea. Finally at 8pm I took 2 Tylenol which helped a lot, but then I worried what if that reduced the effectiveness of the vaccine. I went to bed at 9:15pm and fell asleep right away, but woke up many times soaking wet with sweat. The next day I still had trouble with temperature regulation and I felt very tired and headachy and my L arm still hurt. A few days later I got my menstrual cycle about one week early, and it was the strangest period I've ever had. It was a very light flow, I had lots of clots, and along with the small amount of blood, there was lots of clear stretchy mucous like I get at ovulation. After my first vaccine dose I got my period a few days later also, but that time I only had brown spotting for 4 days and no regular blood flow at all, so this time it was slightly more of a period, but it was really not my usual kind of period. Overall, I felt completely whacked and wrecked by the 2nd dose. It was a terrible experience.
OTHER_MEDS: Vitamins B12, D3, E; Magnesium Glycinate
HISTORY: Fibromyalgia, Anxiety Disorder, I.B.S., migraines, non-restorative sleep disorder
PRIOR_VAX: Already submitted report about 1st vaccine dose.

Medical Summary - Friday, April 9, 2021 Patient received 2nd Moderna vaccination at Care Center. (1st Vaccination at Care Center unremarkable.)  Approximately five minutes after vaccination, seated in Observation area patient leaned forward with elbows on knees, when asked stated he felt light-headed, put his head between his knees, wanted to lie down. He lowered himself to floor, with help transferred to different chair, sipped water, given lollipop, suddenly unresponsive, eyes glazed and rolled back, teeth clenched on lollipop stick, leaning to left side, incontinent of urine, no abnormal arm or leg movements, duration ~ or under 1 minute.   Lollipop removed by staff, vitals: BP 1 Additional information for Item 18: Lollipop removed by staff, vitals: BP 117/72, P68, SpO2 Room Air 96%: now alert and oriented x4, no shortness of breath, no chest discomfort, able to sit in chair without support, was surprised by incontinence. Stated he felt sleepy, tired, and with staff assistance walked to next room for observation where he laid down on carpeted floor. He had no further episode of LOC, remained alert and oriented but continued to feel "tired". No complaints of chest discomfort or shortness of breath. ~ One hour post-incident BP 94/58 with repeat BP 120/82.  ~ Two hours post-incident BP 118/80 (his usual he said) sipped water and electrolytes solution.  Patient verbalized several times this event much different from previous events associated with blood draws which he described like typical vasovagal reactions with recovery within ~ 15 minutes.  Drs. spoke with patient via telephone: PLAN o Can go home today o Do not drive today o Son will pick him up and stay with him for about 24 hours until wife returns from out of town o Appointment scheduled with PA at PMD office for Monday April 12 @ 8:00am � Patient called the office and I listened via speaker, his PMD is out-of-office till later in month, this is first available at the practice o Dr. recommend PMD work-up to also include EEG and CT Scan o R/O vasovagal event v. seizure v. other etiology o Dr. will contact him by phone later today  PA-C MD
