SYMPTOM_TEXT: Description: __On 4/14/2021, Patient arrived for his COVID vaccine. Moderna  lot number 047B21A.  This was his first dose of Moderna. Patient did not disclose to staff any pre-existing medical issues prior to vaccine administration at screening or to nurse prior to administration of vaccine during screening process.  Patient was deemed safe to receive vaccine based on information he provided to both screening nurses and administration nurse.  Vaccine administered by RN into left deltoid via IM injection.  Patient immediately shared he has a history of ?passing out? after injection was provided, information client did not share during original screening process.  Patient then lost consciousness for brief moment.  Onsite contracted paramedics called to assess directly as event unfolded. The RNs notified at assisted directly as well. Client regained consciousness within a few seconds of event Privacy screens were placed for patient dignity and privacy.  Patient assisted to wheelchair by onsite EMS crew.  Patient was then taken to EMS area and further evaluated by onsite EMS crew.  Sheriff Detputy outside area for additional backup if needed. RN remained with EMS crew for duration to assure Public Health RN available for assistance. EMS assisted client to cot and had client lay flat. Vitals assessed with machines. B/P 105/60 initially Patient slow to respond but answered questions appropriately. Patient shared he has been seeing a neurologist for fainting spells and other health issues.  Additionally shared asthma history and is on lisinpril, Advair and Benadryl for allergies.  Took all medications on day of event. Repeat b/b 114/62 pulse ranged from 59-66. O2 sats WNL on room air. EMS placed 12 lead. Patient noted to be in sinus to brady rhythms.  EMS then called the hospital for further evaluation due to patient continuing to remain unstable. Patient was agreeable to transfer to hospital for further eval.  At time of transfer, patient was alert, orientated, and responding.  No IV placed at time o transfer of care to transport.  RN updated team that patient was being transferred to local hospital for further eval.
HISTORY: patient stated after that he has been having issues with syncope.  Has been seeing a neurologist for past few months.  States history of asthma. States history of seasonal allergies.  States past history of fainting with vaccines.  Did not disclose any of the noted information during vaccine screening process.  Did not disclose info to nurse prior to administration of vaccine when prompted about medical history. Offered noted info only after vaccine was administered.

The patient received 1st vaccine dose Saturday afternoon Mar 13.  On Wednesday Mar 17, about mid-day the patient complained of stomach pains believing it to be constipation.  We postponed our dinner, and she laid in bed the rest of the day.  Likely took some Bisacodyl laxative.  The following morning - having worsening pain and what looked like a distended abdomen, we contacted the local 911 to come bring her to the local community emergency room - mid morning.  After about 6 hours they called to tell me that my wife had an ischemic bowel and was being rushed to surgery which happened at about 7:00 pm.  Dr. (surgeon) called to say they removed the gangrenous part of her bowel, and would see on Saturday if the rest of the bowel pinked up.  Unfortunately it did not.  The patient is left with about 2 feet of small bowel, and an ileostomy.  Likely TPN for the remainder of her days.

REACTION AFTER VACCINE INJECTION:  As an aside, I had some unusual reactions to the vaccine immediately after the injections. SYMPTOM_TEXT: an 87 year old male with ESRD on PD, pAfib, CAD, HTN, HLD, hypothyroidism, who was brought in after a witness cardiac arrest.    Patient apparently received the first dose of the Covid vaccine (pfizer) at around 11 am. He was doing fine the rest of the day until later in the evening when he had shortness of breath without chest pain, abdominal pain, nausea, vomiting.    Upon EMS arrival, the patient appeared to have some agonal breathing and then went down, was in PEA arrest, received CPR with 1 dose of calcium, 1 dose of bicarbonate, and 3 doses of epinephrine with return of spontaneous circulation.    Upon arrival in the ED, patient had an intraosseous line, on dopamine for soft blood pressure. Patient has been successfully intubated.
LAB_DATA: ICU admission post PEA arrest.  Pt was septic: per ID notes: It remains uncertain what happened.  The polymicrobial bacteremia and candidemia favors GI/hepatobiliary sepsis.  However contrast-enhanced CT of the abdomen and pelvis yesterday does not show any obvious indication of anatomic abnormality.  CT of the chest does not reveal any evidence of pneumonia.   He has not improved despite aggressive polymicrobial therapy.  He is not making urine and is building up acid.  His chance of survival is minimal.   In retrospect it does not appear that this is a side effect of COVID-19 vaccination as he is found to have multiple organisms in the blood.  Vancomycin is no longer indicated and can be stopped.  He also does not need any further tobramycin.  Zosyn and anidulafungin are all that is required here based on the culture results.
OTHER_MEDS: amiodarone (PACERONE) 100 mg Oral Tablet     Sig: TAKE 1/2 TABLET BY MOUTH DAILY budesonide/formoterol (SYMBICORT) 160-4.5 mcg/actuation Inhalation HFA Aerosol Inhaler     Sig: Inhale  by mouth. clopidogrel 75 mg Oral Tablet     Sig: Take 7

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I had a strong reaction to the shot of the expected reactions. However, I also had  - -  I began to have symptoms the next day that I was having an allergic reaction and hives were coming on. About 5 hours after shot, I started feeling weak, tired, and nauseas with a slight headache.  I had discomfort trying to fall asleep. I woke up at 12:43AM with a throbbing headache. I was hospitalized at 18 for viral meningitis, and this was a similar, intense pain. It felt like I had a crown on,  and that crown on my head caused a very intense, throbbing, debilitating pain. I also had chattering teeth, shaking with a freezing fever. I eventually fell asleep and woke up again at 2-something. My fever and headache still intense, but now I was drenched in sweat and burning up. I wanted to get up and find my thermometer--I remember digging through my drawers and closets around my apartment,  I remember speaking but no recollection what I was trying to say (I live alone), and I remember seeing my reflection looking glazed over. I don't remember getting back in bed but woke up again after 5AM. I still had a bad headache, though less severe, and felt my body was alternating very hot sweating and very cold freezing--like it was mix and matching. I eventually fell asleep again and woke up around 7:45AM. I was fatigued with a fever and chills all day.  I found my thermometer and went to sleep with a 100.3 fever that night. I was much better next day, just slight fatigue.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: The patient is a poor historian and history is obtained from him and his partner.  His symptoms have started yesterday after receiving the second dose of a Covid vaccine.  The couple went to eat a meal of Chinese food, and that evening the patient developed persistent nausea and vomiting.  He had multiple episodes of emesis.  According to his partner, he continued to have episodes of emesis this morning.  The emesis was nonbilious and nonbloody, described as watery.    The patient says he woke up this morning and may have felt some palpitations.  He thinks the palpitations may have been worse than usual.  He says he generally just felt unwell.  He could not get out of bed and move around very much due to the nausea and vomiting.  He says that for this reason, he activated EMS who brought him to the hospital.  Regarding his atrial fibrillation, he says he is mostly compliant with taking his medications, however he did not take any of his home medications today.In the ER, he was hypertensive to 141/111 and tachycardic to 141, tachypneic to 23.  His heart rate went up to the 170s and he was given multiple doses of IV metoprolol.  On labs, he had a leukocytosis with a white blood count of 12 and the D-dimer was elevated greater than 20.  CTA was obtained to rule out pulmonary embolism which was negative.  However, down in the scanner he developed an episode of unresponsiveness with questionable seizure symptoms.  He was treated with an LR bolus 500 cc but due to the findings of increased pulmonary vascular congestion, was diuresed with Lasix 80 mg IV x1.  Blood cultures x2 were obtained.
LAB_DATA: Lengthy Admission x30d  PRINCIPAL DIAGNOSIS:  #. Atrial fibrillation with RVR #. Hyponatremia secondary to SIADH  #. Seizure disorder with breakthrough seizures on AED   SECONDARY DIAGNOSES:  - Acute gastroenteritis secondary to Covid vaccination, resolved Problem list 1. Complex partial seizure, due to potential leptomeningeal carcinomatosis 2. Hyponatremia due to SIADH 3. Permanent atrial fibrillation with RVR 4. stageIV castrate resistant prostate cancer with osseous metastasis to R thigh 5. Chronic anemia due to malignancy 6. Chronic HFrEF with recovered EF 7. Convulsive syncope due to tachyarrhythmia 8. Orthostatic hypotension due to autonomic insufficiency 9. Severe protein calorie malnutrition   His hospital course was prolonged due to complex seizure and difficult to treat SIADH.  Finally with uptitrating Vimpat and adding Keppra he remained seizure-free and with tolvaptan, demeclocycline his sodium level remained stable.  LP was declined so we could not confirm whether he has leptomeningeal carcinomatosis, but the clinical picture raises high suspicion.
OTHER_MEDS: Metoprolol succinate XL 150 mg daily 2.  Digoxin 0.125 mg p.o. daily 3.  Ferrous sulfate 324 mg p.o. daily 4.  Keppra 1000 mg p.o. twice daily 5.  Decadron 4 mg p.o. twice daily 6.  Tylenol 1000 mg p.o. 3 times daily 7.  Duloxetine 60 mg p.
CUR_ILL: He denies any recent illnesses or infections.  He denies any fevers or chills.  He is not having any chest pain or shortness of breath.  He denies any orthopnea, paroxysmal nocturnal dyspnea, or peripheral edema.  He says his cancer pain is well controlled on the current outpatient pain regimen.  The Decadron in particular which was recently prescribed seems to be really helping.
HISTORY: Patient is an 69 year old male with permanent atrial fibrillation not on anticoagulation, heart failure with reduced ejection fraction recovered 50-55% (2/4/2021), metastatic castrate resistant prostate cancer complicated by right femur pathologic fracture, chronic cancer pain and opioid-induced constipation, who presents with acute onset of feeling unwell.

My wife drove me to ER at 12:30 AM Thursday.

* MAR 8th = Vaccine shot * MAR 15th = alleged "sore throat" * MAR 19th = watery eyes; dry eyes;  tired eyes.  Onset of right eye not blinking/closing. * MAR 21st = Emergency Room.  Diagnosed w/ BELLS PALSY.  [Ruled out stroke]  The following week after my vaccination (approximately MAR 15th), I experienced a strange feeling at the back of my throat.  It can best described as a "sore throat".  I noticed it upon waking up.   I could feel it at the back of my throat when swallowing;  the act of swallowing would enable me to "feel" the sensation at the back of my throat.  This was unusual and not normal for me.  I thought I was coming down with a cold virus.  I had not been sick for over a year and thought it was a strange feeling.  I was concerned.  With the recent schools, restaurants, and gyms opening up with less restrictions, I learned from coworkers that there was an increase of illnesses  because our immune systems are not as strong and germs are easily transferable during the usual interactions.  Therefore, I expected my sore throat to be the start of a harmless cold virus.   Then, later in the week (MAR 19th), I noticed my eyes were abnormally dripping tears.  It is my experience that I get this effect in the office setting or during winter when my eyes are "dry".  However, I was neither in the workplace (office), nor was it winter.  I was not sure why my eyes had excessive tears coming out.  Finally, on SUN (MAR 21st), an obvious physical symptom finally became apparent to me and my family members.  My speech was impaired.  I could not chew properly.  I could not drink from a cup.  I struggled during breakfast.  I was not sure if I was having a STROKE.  I recited the alphabet to hear for a slurred speech.  I looked in the mirror, and my smile was not perfect.   I got dressed and went to the Emergency Room.   The doctors performed physical PUSH-PULL tests, eye tests, etc.   DIAGNOSIS = Bells Palsy.     OTHER SYMPTOMS = + shortness of breath.  + leg swelling.  + headaches.  + excruciating pain in the neck, especially during sleep (laying down).
LAB_DATA: * MAR 21st = Emergency Room.  Diagnosed w/ BELLS PALSY.   * APR 1st = first available date to be seen by my Primary Care Physician (PCP).   She examined me for BELLS PALSY.  Doctor referred me to a NEUROLOGIST.   * MAY 3rd = first available date to be seen by Specialist Doctor.   Still waiting for appointment date.
OTHER_MEDS: Simvastatin, Losartan, Metformin, Amlodipine.   4 TOTAL, everyday.
HISTORY: High blood pressure.  Obesity.  Borderline diabetic (A1C = 7)

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Shot on 29MAR21. First lethargy began 31MAR21, followed by mild chills 01APR21. Over the weekend the symptoms waned and seemed to be subsiding. Wednesday of the following week, 07APR21 the chills became increasingly unpleasant especially at night requiring two extra blankets. Sharp pain radiating horizontally along the "hip-girdle" and up along the spine on the right side began that night. In the morning the top of my head was painfully sensitive to touch (like it is when I have the flu), I was slightly groggy and while the chills had subsided the hip & back pain remained. I went to work thinking I might be passing a kidney stone as the symptoms were similar in location & intensity as when I passed a stone in 2003. The chills became so severe I was wearing my jacket in my office and that's when I made an appointment at a local Urgent Care facility to see if they could perform an ultrasound for stones. When the scan proved negative, I had to assume I was experiencing side-effects from the vaccine. The symptoms diminished considerably by Sunday, so I returned to work Monday 12APR21 with no other issues.

On Tuesday, February 16, I received my 1st Moderna Covid vaccine. On Tuesday, March 16, I received my 2nd Moderna Covid vaccine at 11AM and Eylea shots (one in each eye) at 2PM. I have been receiving Eylea every 3 months for about 3 years in one or both eyes.   On Saturday, March 20 at about 11:30AM, while sitting at traffic light, I saw what appeared to be a translucent sheet of plastic cover the left driver's window and the left half of the windshield. This was only visible in the left eye. Twenty seconds later, a yellow opaqueness developed in the left eye, which eventually cleared, but vision was still blurry. When I got home, I called my retinologist. He recommended I go into a dark room and close my eyes. At this time, I had white translucent vision in the lower left quadrant of vision in both eyes. My retinologist sent me to Hospital Emergency Department, which is part of Hospital. After being assess at Eye Emergency Room, I was admitted to Hospital for a right occipital lobe stroke that was confirmed by multiple MRIs of the head. I was told that I was experiencing an ocular migraine (although I had no pain.) I was discharged on Monday, March 22, on Eliquis. As of April 15, all of the yellow opaque and white translucent visions are gone. However my left eye vision remains blurred and hazy. I have since been diagnosed with age-related cataracts in both eyes and a fast-moving cataract in top portion of left lens. I will also report this occurrence to the reporting system.
OTHER_MEDS: Metoprolol Tartrate 100mg BID, Lisinopril 20mg BID, CoEnzyme Q 200mg daily, AREDS 2 Multivitamin BID, Multivitamin daily, Fish Oil daily, Vitamin E daily, Glucosamine Chondroitin MSM BID

I went to bed shortly afterwards.  On Sunday,Easter morning April 4, at 6:30am I woke up with a very severe case of vertigo (Meniere's Disease).  It lasted about 3 hours of sever heaving and extreme dizziness.  I could not cope and had to just lay there not knowing what was wrong/going on.  It finally went away after about 3 hours.  The next morning, Mon. Apr 5, I called my Dr  to make an appointment and went in 2 days later.  There were no other cases of it and he could not figure what caused it and I either could I.  So far so good that I have not had another reaction and feel fine today after nearly 3 weeks.  :-)

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Employee taken to the ED.  52 y.o. female presenting with numbness and tingling around her throat, tongue, and lips after receiving the first dose of the Pfizer covid vaccine at approximately 12:15 pm and subsequently was sent to the ED about a half hour later. She stated that after receiving the vaccine, her tongue felt "full" and her lips had some tingling - overall it just felt funny. She received 50 mg of Benadryl - this made the numbness and tingling decrease slightly but it hasn't caused it to completely resolve. She also had a slight headache that started shortly after this. She denied any shortness of breath or rash. She has never had any symptoms like this with a previous vaccine although she has had urticaria with penicillins
LAB_DATA: Triage notes and patient's vital signs were reviewed. Patient was evaluated by medical student, resident and attending physician.  Vital signs were unremarkable, and physical examination was unremarkable.  A broad differential of possible diagnoses were considered for this patient's presenting symptoms, including mild adverse allergic reaction to the vaccine and possible angioedema. Angioedema is less likely as patient's throat is not swollen, doesn't have shortness of breath and she is able to talk.   While in the emergency department, the patient's clinical status was closely monitored including her respiratory status and serial exams of the posterior oropharynx. She received decadron and had improvement, with no clinical worsening though symptoms do persist somewhat. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Nearly 25 days after receiving my 1st Moderna vaccine I woke up on Easter morning with a very stiff Right wrist.  By 1pm that day I was experiencing a lot of swelling and found it difficult to prepare food for a picnic we were going to. By 4pm that day I had to wrap my hand in ice, thinking it would provide some relief and took 2 Tylenol. By about 6:30 my husband and son were taking me to ER and on the way my Left hand began to swell and experience similar pain. By the time we arrived at the ER I was in excruciating pain in my entire hand up to my elbow and it felt like fire was burning through a vein up my arm. I had no use of my fingers which had stiffened and appeared maimed.  After blood work, assessment, pain medication and steroid injection I was released with no real answers. other than to see my physician for follow-up.  I was given a 12 RX for steroids which helped after the 4th day.  I saw Dr. today, as she had been on vacation all last week.  We discussed the possibility of an adverse reaction to the Moderna vaccine, and she recommended that I submit my information to you.  4/15/2021
LAB_DATA: April 4, 2021 blood work performed at  Hospital - date of occurrence and nothing was revealed to be out of the ordinary.

DIAGNOSIS: 1. Superficial thrombophlebitis MEDICAL DECISION MAKING/DIFFERENTIAL DX: Differential diagnosis includes DVT, superficial thrombophlebitis, muscle strain, tendinitis. The patient presented to the emergency department with atraumatic left leg pain. An ultrasound reveals a fairly large blood clot in the greater saphenous vein. Although this is a superficial clot, given its extent, I think it warrants anticoagulation. Per the trial, the patient would benefit from 45 days of 10 mg Xarelto treatment. The patient was given good precautions regarding bleeding risk while on a blood thinner. He will schedule follow-up appoint with his primary care doctor. He will also use Tylenol and warm packs to help with the discomfort from the superficial thrombophlebitis. He was discharged in satisfactory condition.

Started experiencing some dizziness on March 8th that lasted for approximately 3 weeks. Did get the second dose of the Pfizer vaccine and a week later felt a sort of hot feeling in my head similar to that ballon sensation when first coming down with the flu but nowhere near as intense. The dizziness was worst on March 10th then slowly resolved itself over the next few weeks. It was mild to moderate in intensity, I could feel a continuation of movement after turning my head sideways, it felt like the head was still going. Strange. I was still able to go to work but the effect was noticable. The only variables in my life recently were beginning Humira on Feb 2nd 2021 and getting the series of Pfizer Covid vaccines on Feb 19 and March 12. I did notify my gasteroenterologist because at first I assumed it was the Humira. He said that is not a side effect. On further research I have seen a lot of people reporting vertigo several weeks out after the Covid shots as if the antibody formation produces and inflammatory response in the ear in some patients. Unknown the symptoms are related to the shot or not. I had one outbreak of Meniere's Disease in 2006 and has not recurred. Perhaps the vaccine can cause a recurrance?

This patient came in to the community center to receive his 2nd dose of his Pfizer vaccine at approx 10:06am. At approx 10 minutes after sitting in the observation area, the patient started to fee hot, dizzy, some tunneled vision and nausea. This attendee did not have any sort of reaction to his first dose. This was brought to the attention of one of the observing staff members. This nurse,  was called over to the patient. The attendee was asked to lay down on the cot provided and we elevated his legs. RN, measured his vital signs: bp 110/70, HR: 60, Resp 16, O2 97%. This patient denied any shortness of breath. Lung sounds were clear, and no wheezing or rhonchi were observed. This patient stated he has a history of Asthma and took his asthma medications this morning as normally directed. This patient was directed to lay down for approx 10 minutes, then stated he felt much better and wanted to sit up and take a sip of water. The attendee tolerated the water well. This nurse, advised for this attendee to stay for another 10 minutes until he had no symptoms present. The patient quickly felt better and stated that his wife was out in the car and would be driving him home. This nurse advised for him to go to the Emergency Room if he felt any of these symptoms again.

Focal area of prior cortical injury involving the right precentral gyrus, possibly accounting for the patient's left hand weakness.  No acute hemorrhage. No herniation. Brain is normal in volume for age. No reduced diffusion or abnormal susceptibility.  Ventricles within normal limits of size for age. No extra-axial collection.  IMPRESSION:  No acute intracranial abnormalities. Evidence of prior white matter injury, could be related to demyelinating disease, and prior injury to the right precentral gyrus possibly accounting for left hand weakness.  (Report dictated by: MD, Department of Radiology and Biomedical Imaging) Addendum Evaluation of the dural venous sinuses demonstrates nonocclusive thrombus in the right sigmoid sinus, which extends to the right jugular vein. Correlate with imaging of the jugular vein. (Addended by, MD on 3/4/2021)
